anDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50056"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man undergoes removal of right chest melanoma on a background of previous skin cancers. The surgeon also dissects the right axillary lymph nodes draining the chest to prevent further metastasis. On post-operative examination, the surgeon observes impaired abduction of the right arm beyond 90 degrees and a deformity (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves most likely has been injured?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Axillary nerve","Intercostobrachial nerve","Thoracodorsal nerve","Lower subscapular nerve","Long thoracic nerve"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elong thoracic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (C5, C6, C7) has most likely been injured intra-operatively. This is a known complication of axillary lymph node dissection (\u0026lt;1%). The long thoracic nerve travels distal and laterally deep to the clavicle and superficial to the first and second ribs (making it exposed for potential injury). The terminal branches innervate the serratus anterior muscle, which draws the scapula forward and upward and helps abduct the scapula. As such, injury to this nerve will cause impaired arm abduction alongside a protruding scapula (medial border) owing to its unopposed action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles and is responsible for shoulder abduction and sensation over the deltoid region. Injury to this nerve would not cause scapular winging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eintercostobrachial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides sensory innervation to the skin of the upper medial arm and axilla. Injury to this nerve would not cause scapular winging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ethoracodorsal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the latissimus dorsi muscle, which extends, adducts, and rotates the humerus. Injury to this nerve would not cause scapular winging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elower subscapular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the lower part of the subscapularis muscle and the teres major muscle, both involved in internal rotation and adduction of the shoulder. Injury to this nerve would not cause scapular winging.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The long thoracic nerve (C5, C6, C7) innervates the serratus anterior muscle.","Damage to the long thoracic nerve can cause paralysis to the serratus anterior manifesting as \u0022winging of the scapula\u0022."],"references":["Anson BJ, McVay CB. Thoracic walls: Breast or mammary region. In: Surgical Anatomy, 6th ed, Anson BJ, McVay CB (Eds), Saunders, 1984. p.357.","Ung O, Tan M, Chua B, Barraclough B. Complete axillary dissection: a technique that still has relevance in contemporary management of breast cancer. ANZ J Surg 2006; 76:518. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16768781/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35331"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11669"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15167"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15167"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/770616d0-6cc0-4b0c-9c24-02d18b0e6ffd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/770616d0-6cc0-4b0c-9c24-02d18b0e6ffd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":532}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35331"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-06T21:39:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-06T21:41:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4290"}},"content":{"data":{"type"